15
00:00:32,817 --> 00:00:41,140
[SPEAKER_02]: There will be a meeting of the Medford City Council committee the whole on Wednesday, April 26 2023 at 6pm, the Medford City Council chamber on the second floor of Medford City Hall and via zoom.

16
00:00:41,530 --> 00:00:46,713
[SPEAKER_02]: The purpose of this meeting is to discuss the capital improvement plan presentation, paper 23-073.

17
00:00:47,193 --> 00:00:51,376
[SPEAKER_02]: The committee has invited Mayor Brianna Longo-Kern and Chief of Staff Nina Nazarian to attend this meeting.

18
00:00:51,956 --> 00:00:55,338
[SPEAKER_02]: For further information, aids and accommodations, contact the city clerk at 781-393-2425.

19
00:00:55,458 --> 00:00:59,100
[SPEAKER_02]: Sincerely yours, Nicole Murrell, Council President.

20
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:02,062
[SPEAKER_02]: The meeting notice says just what we're here for.

21
00:01:02,102 --> 00:01:11,127
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe actually in lieu of members of the administration, we'd have Sarah Kincannon from the Collins Center, who is able to give us a presentation on the capital improvement plan

22
00:01:12,062 --> 00:01:16,164
[SPEAKER_02]: Sarah, I believe you should have the ability to share your screen at this point.

23
00:01:18,745 --> 00:01:19,126
[SPEAKER_03]: Excellent.

24
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:19,626
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

25
00:01:19,726 --> 00:01:23,788
[SPEAKER_03]: Let me share my screen.

26
00:01:36,354 --> 00:01:36,974
[SPEAKER_03]: How does that look?

27
00:01:36,994 --> 00:01:37,835
[SPEAKER_03]: Can everyone see it?

28
00:01:37,915 --> 00:01:38,695
[SPEAKER_03]: And is it big enough?

29
00:01:39,976 --> 00:01:40,596
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes and yes.

30
00:01:41,830 --> 00:01:42,290
[SPEAKER_06]: Excellent.

31
00:01:43,031 --> 00:01:46,634
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you think it would be possible to forward a copy of the presentation to the city clerk?

32
00:01:46,835 --> 00:01:50,598
[SPEAKER_04]: We just haven't received it in any form other than we're about to receive it from you.

33
00:01:50,638 --> 00:01:53,701
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'd love to be able to take a look at it after the meeting.

34
00:01:54,722 --> 00:01:55,603
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, absolutely.

35
00:01:55,623 --> 00:01:56,363
[SPEAKER_03]: I can do that.

36
00:01:57,364 --> 00:01:57,765
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

37
00:01:58,125 --> 00:01:59,066
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll write myself a note.

38
00:02:05,231 --> 00:02:05,672
[SPEAKER_03]: All right.

39
00:02:06,813 --> 00:02:07,714
[SPEAKER_03]: Shall I just get started?

40
00:02:08,993 --> 00:02:09,473
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, please.

41
00:02:09,593 --> 00:02:09,894
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

42
00:02:10,154 --> 00:02:10,674
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

43
00:02:10,974 --> 00:02:11,455
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

44
00:02:12,015 --> 00:02:13,476
[SPEAKER_03]: So good evening, everyone.

45
00:02:13,837 --> 00:02:25,986
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you to the city council for giving me the opportunity to come before you tonight to provide a high level overview of the capital improvement plan that I have been assisting the city to develop.

46
00:02:26,826 --> 00:02:35,473
[SPEAKER_03]: I've prepared several slides that kind of walk through the process and some of the results of the work that we've been doing in the city.

47
00:02:37,394 --> 00:02:41,559
[SPEAKER_03]: And so at the end of the PowerPoint, I'd be happy to take any questions that you have.

48
00:02:41,659 --> 00:02:44,882
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm not sure if Bob Dickinson is in the room.

49
00:02:46,484 --> 00:02:50,968
[SPEAKER_03]: He may also be available if he's there to answer any questions that you may have.

50
00:02:51,469 --> 00:02:55,033
[SPEAKER_02]: He's not physically here at the moment, but we were expecting him, so we will see.

51
00:02:55,698 --> 00:02:56,599
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, excellent.

52
00:02:57,219 --> 00:03:06,648
[SPEAKER_03]: At any point in the presentation, if you have questions and you want to, you know, ask, feel free to just kind of say, hey, I have a question.

53
00:03:07,809 --> 00:03:12,513
[SPEAKER_03]: Your videos are quite small on my screen, so I may not see you waving your hand or anything like that.

54
00:03:13,529 --> 00:03:14,049
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, great.

55
00:03:15,109 --> 00:03:18,250
[SPEAKER_03]: So just one quick note before we get started.

56
00:03:18,350 --> 00:03:25,052
[SPEAKER_03]: So the plan that I have been helping the city to complete is an FY23 through FY28 plan.

57
00:03:26,692 --> 00:03:31,253
[SPEAKER_03]: We typically would do a five-year plan, but in this case, we decided to do a six-year plan.

58
00:03:31,313 --> 00:03:35,554
[SPEAKER_03]: And that really had to do with the timing of when we were doing the work.

59
00:03:36,734 --> 00:03:42,396
[SPEAKER_03]: We thought since FY23 is nearly over, we will extend it to six years that way.

60
00:03:43,801 --> 00:03:44,714
[SPEAKER_03]: it would be a complete plan.

61
00:03:48,761 --> 00:03:52,602
[SPEAKER_03]: So just by way of introduction, I want to introduce myself and the Collins Center.

62
00:03:53,042 --> 00:04:02,066
[SPEAKER_03]: So as the Council President said, my name is Sarah Concanon, and I am the Director of Municipal Services at the Collins Center for Public Management at UMass Boston.

63
00:04:02,586 --> 00:04:15,130
[SPEAKER_03]: The Collins Center was established in 2008 by the state legislature at UMass Boston to provide affordable and practical consulting and technical assistance to cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

64
00:04:15,490 --> 00:04:23,600
[SPEAKER_03]: We also work with regional governments, school districts, state agencies, and any other public sector entity that is in furtherance of our mission.

65
00:04:26,352 --> 00:04:36,838
[SPEAKER_03]: Two years ago, the city of Medford worked with me to receive a grant through the Community Compact Best Practices Program to develop a capital improvement plan.

66
00:04:38,779 --> 00:04:44,983
[SPEAKER_03]: A year ago, the mayor asked me to come back and help her and her administration

67
00:04:45,943 --> 00:04:49,525
[SPEAKER_03]: update the plan with the department heads.

68
00:04:50,025 --> 00:04:57,868
[SPEAKER_03]: And so what I've been doing for the past year is sort of managing the process so that we can get to an updated capital plan.

69
00:05:00,409 --> 00:05:06,772
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to just briefly for anybody who's watching who isn't familiar, just go through a few definitions.

70
00:05:06,852 --> 00:05:12,614
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I know the counselors know this, but what is a capital project and what is a capital improvement plan?

71
00:05:13,214 --> 00:05:22,478
[SPEAKER_03]: So a capital project is typically a major non-recurring expense with a cost of at least $10,000 and a useful life of at least five years.

72
00:05:23,058 --> 00:05:35,973
[SPEAKER_03]: The $10,000 threshold is a little bit low for a city of Medford size, but nonetheless, we thought using a lower threshold would make sense because we didn't want any projects that were in the $10,000, $20,000 range to get lost.

73
00:05:37,315 --> 00:05:40,279
[SPEAKER_03]: So that is how we define a capital project.

74
00:05:41,624 --> 00:05:50,531
[SPEAKER_03]: A capital improvement plan is a multi-year plan that is comprehensive in the sense that it covers all funding sources and all departments in the city.

75
00:05:51,032 --> 00:05:52,793
[SPEAKER_03]: And it's also financially viable.

76
00:05:53,274 --> 00:05:58,618
[SPEAKER_03]: So this is something that the call-in center really pushes our clients to think about.

77
00:05:58,938 --> 00:06:07,526
[SPEAKER_03]: What we don't wanna do is spend a year developing a wishlist that will never be funded because that's not really the purpose of a plan.

78
00:06:07,806 --> 00:06:10,288
[SPEAKER_03]: The plan is supposed to be there so that residents can know

79
00:06:10,748 --> 00:06:16,371
[SPEAKER_03]: and expect that there's going to be certain investments in their schools, in their roads, in their water system.

80
00:06:16,891 --> 00:06:26,416
[SPEAKER_03]: It also exists so that the finance team in the city can make appropriate decisions about issuing debt, about revenue, and about the operating budget, and so on.

81
00:06:26,936 --> 00:06:33,380
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's really important that that third bullet is achieved when you're going through a capital improvement planning process.

82
00:06:33,960 --> 00:06:37,622
[SPEAKER_03]: If you don't achieve that, it's really not a plan, it's simply a wish list.

83
00:06:43,828 --> 00:06:54,831
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, for any members of the public who might be learning about a CIP for the first time tonight, it's a really important document and it's an important process for a city or town to go through.

84
00:06:55,271 --> 00:06:59,012
[SPEAKER_03]: If you don't have a capital plan, there are a lot of things that can go wrong.

85
00:06:59,472 --> 00:07:03,493
[SPEAKER_03]: So for example, there could be negative impacts to public health or public safety.

86
00:07:04,393 --> 00:07:11,435
[SPEAKER_03]: I think about, for example, an intersection that is not well-designed or maybe has not been updated in many, many decades.

87
00:07:11,715 --> 00:07:13,096
[SPEAKER_03]: It could be a public safety issue.

88
00:07:13,196 --> 00:07:21,200
[SPEAKER_03]: And so making sure that you get those types of projects on your list that are going to improve public health, improve public safety is important.

89
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:24,641
[SPEAKER_03]: There's also a certain degree of exposure to legal liability.

90
00:07:24,701 --> 00:07:34,566
[SPEAKER_03]: If you're not investing in your facilities, if you have roads and sidewalks and facilities that are in disrepair, it could expose the city to legal liability.

91
00:07:35,790 --> 00:07:38,673
[SPEAKER_03]: It could also create staff inefficiency and ineffectiveness.

92
00:07:39,654 --> 00:07:46,700
[SPEAKER_03]: The best example that we hear all the time at the call-in center when we work with our clients is about vehicles.

93
00:07:47,221 --> 00:07:54,407
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, public works staff are out in the field on the day-to-day and if they don't have vehicles that can work that

94
00:07:55,288 --> 00:08:01,615
[SPEAKER_03]: can offer heating and cooling and aren't in the shop, then that makes them really inefficient.

95
00:08:02,035 --> 00:08:16,912
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's important to make sure that the tools that the staff have are up to date and periodically reinvested or rehabilitated so that they can be used to the highest degree of effectiveness.

96
00:08:18,525 --> 00:08:22,967
[SPEAKER_03]: The other thing that a CIP really should help you avoid is costly emergency repairs.

97
00:08:23,528 --> 00:08:36,454
[SPEAKER_03]: So if you have a school building and you know that the roof is 20 years old, you better start taking a look and inspecting it to make sure that you know when it needs to be replaced.

98
00:08:36,614 --> 00:08:45,498
[SPEAKER_03]: If you don't, and there is a catastrophic leak, you would be forced to make an emergency repair, most likely at significant cost.

99
00:08:48,052 --> 00:08:53,016
[SPEAKER_03]: Another potential pitfall of not having a CIP is poorly managed or poorly timed projects.

100
00:08:53,477 --> 00:09:00,463
[SPEAKER_03]: And the classic example is you have a water main that needs to be replaced.

101
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:04,004
[SPEAKER_03]: and you have a road that needs to be reconstructed.

102
00:09:04,344 --> 00:09:11,653
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, you should do the water main first and then the road, because if you do the road and then you need to make a repair on the water main, you're going to have to dig up the road.

103
00:09:12,033 --> 00:09:22,505
[SPEAKER_03]: And so the timing of projects can be quite complicated in a municipality, and so it's really important to have a plan that thinks through the phasing of certain projects.

104
00:09:24,431 --> 00:09:35,019
[SPEAKER_03]: Another issue with not having a robust capital improvement plan is you may have inconsistent debt service, which is really difficult to accommodate in an operating budget.

105
00:09:35,060 --> 00:09:41,725
[SPEAKER_03]: You don't want your debt service to be a million dollars one year and then 750 the next and then one and a half million.

106
00:09:41,985 --> 00:09:44,027
[SPEAKER_03]: You really want smooth debt service.

107
00:09:44,087 --> 00:09:44,867
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's the best

108
00:09:46,048 --> 00:09:48,670
[SPEAKER_03]: approach from a financial perspective.

109
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:55,334
[SPEAKER_03]: And so planning helps you make sure that you can maintain that consistent debt service year over year.

110
00:09:57,196 --> 00:10:03,638
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the last one on here is general financial disorder and negative impacts on bond ratings.

111
00:10:03,678 --> 00:10:18,121
[SPEAKER_03]: So the rating agencies that determine a city or town's bond ratings do look to see whether the city or town has a capital improvement plan, along with a lot of other things like a financial forecast, financial policies, etc.

112
00:10:18,881 --> 00:10:23,786
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's an indicator to the credit rating agencies that the city is well run.

113
00:10:23,886 --> 00:10:28,691
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's really important that the city maintain an up-to-date, robust capital improvement plan.

114
00:10:33,996 --> 00:10:37,279
[SPEAKER_03]: So this is a typical capital improvement planning process.

115
00:10:39,158 --> 00:10:39,658
[SPEAKER_03]: for the city.

116
00:10:40,379 --> 00:10:55,025
[SPEAKER_03]: So sometime typically in late summer or early fall, the administration and finance teams would develop what we call a capital investment strategy, which is based on a financial forecast and projected resources.

117
00:10:55,725 --> 00:11:04,527
[SPEAKER_03]: The capital investment strategy is really the financial plan in terms of how much money is available to be invested in capital.

118
00:11:04,587 --> 00:11:10,168
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm going to talk more specifically about what the capital investment strategy is, and I'd be happy to answer any questions.

119
00:11:11,408 --> 00:11:22,670
[SPEAKER_03]: Part of what they'll look at when they're developing the investment strategy is the historical spending, the historical budget, and looking at projecting what the operating budget is going to be out in the future.

120
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:37,230
[SPEAKER_03]: And then in the fall, all the departments are going to be surveyed so that the city can understand capital needs, understand the priorities, and understand what grant opportunities are out there.

121
00:11:37,791 --> 00:11:41,053
[SPEAKER_03]: So the department heads are a really integral part of the process.

122
00:11:41,774 --> 00:11:47,779
[SPEAKER_03]: And I can't really stress enough how much work the department heads have done

123
00:11:49,380 --> 00:12:05,929
[SPEAKER_03]: Over the last year on this capital improvement plan, they really are providing so much information, and I really want to commend them all because they were all wonderful to work with.

124
00:12:07,289 --> 00:12:17,715
[SPEAKER_03]: In early winter, the project requests are reviewed and assessed for their adherence to citywide goals and priorities, and the capital investment strategy is finalized.

125
00:12:18,568 --> 00:12:20,580
[SPEAKER_03]: So one note on priorities.

126
00:12:23,435 --> 00:12:32,062
[SPEAKER_03]: It's the department heads who are providing really good information about what the top priorities are for their departments.

127
00:12:32,923 --> 00:12:46,634
[SPEAKER_03]: And that is invaluable because in a city the size of Medford, it's nearly impossible for one person to fully understand all the priorities that are going on.

128
00:12:47,094 --> 00:12:52,399
[SPEAKER_03]: So we really rely on the department heads and take into consideration what they're telling us the priorities are.

129
00:12:54,690 --> 00:12:58,753
[SPEAKER_03]: So, and then also in early winter, the capital investment strategy is finalized.

130
00:12:58,793 --> 00:13:12,704
[SPEAKER_03]: Sometimes there's more information that will inform the capital investment strategy, things like developments in the operating budget process or information coming out of the state in terms of their own budgeting process.

131
00:13:14,509 --> 00:13:29,879
[SPEAKER_03]: Then in the spring the capital plan is finalized and presented to city council, and then on an ongoing basis, the administration and finance staff need to provide oversight, while the departments are initiating and managing the projects, you know that is a really important.

132
00:13:30,900 --> 00:13:34,942
[SPEAKER_03]: piece of capital planning that doesn't get talked about a lot.

133
00:13:35,523 --> 00:13:38,204
[SPEAKER_03]: Once you have the plan, it's time to execute on the plan.

134
00:13:38,744 --> 00:13:48,429
[SPEAKER_03]: And so one of the considerations that I always need to think of and I need to communicate is, what are departments able to manage in terms of projects?

135
00:13:48,690 --> 00:13:54,473
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some departments, planning departments, DPWs, engineering.

136
00:13:54,833 --> 00:13:58,515
[SPEAKER_03]: There are a lot of projects that they see as needed.

137
00:13:59,275 --> 00:14:06,466
[SPEAKER_03]: And sometimes you don't have the staff resources to manage all those projects, let alone the funding to actually pay for them.

138
00:14:06,807 --> 00:14:08,088
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's an important consideration.

139
00:14:09,845 --> 00:14:16,910
[SPEAKER_03]: I will say that the project plan, which is the list of projects, is really a dynamic document.

140
00:14:17,951 --> 00:14:21,093
[SPEAKER_03]: Priorities can change, resources can change.

141
00:14:21,874 --> 00:14:30,420
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's really important that the capital planning process be considered an ongoing annual process, just like you would an operating budget.

142
00:14:34,743 --> 00:14:36,884
[SPEAKER_02]: Sarah, we have a question from Vice President Behrs.

143
00:14:37,384 --> 00:14:37,945
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, excellent.

144
00:14:39,917 --> 00:14:41,798
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi Sarah, thanks for the presentation so far.

145
00:14:43,018 --> 00:14:49,780
[SPEAKER_04]: I just have a question on the survey of capital needs and opportunities.

146
00:14:51,620 --> 00:15:05,124
[SPEAKER_04]: Could you go a little bit more into how the process occurred, and were there like standard operating practices that the call and center recommended to the city to conduct that process and then also to conduct the annual review, and then I have a follow up after that.

147
00:15:06,143 --> 00:15:12,241
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so what we did this year is take the list of capital needs

148
00:15:14,095 --> 00:15:16,637
[SPEAKER_03]: which I typically will call the capital needs assessment.

149
00:15:17,437 --> 00:15:21,419
[SPEAKER_03]: And that is basically a big spreadsheet of all of the projects.

150
00:15:22,580 --> 00:15:26,162
[SPEAKER_03]: And we send that back out to departments.

151
00:15:26,302 --> 00:15:29,644
[SPEAKER_03]: And we say, what has stayed the same?

152
00:15:30,345 --> 00:15:31,305
[SPEAKER_03]: What has changed?

153
00:15:31,606 --> 00:15:40,651
[SPEAKER_03]: Whether it is the scope of a project that's changed, whether it is the cost of a project that's changed, maybe last year,

154
00:15:42,852 --> 00:15:55,018
[SPEAKER_03]: engineering told us that they were going to reconstruct a road, but now they realize they can only afford a smaller section or they need more money to do the full section.

155
00:15:56,438 --> 00:16:02,661
[SPEAKER_03]: Project scope can change, project costs can change, and priorities can change.

156
00:16:02,801 --> 00:16:06,563
[SPEAKER_03]: Basically, what we did was send that information back out to department heads and said,

157
00:16:07,423 --> 00:16:19,562
[SPEAKER_03]: please let us know what has changed and add any projects that you weren't aware of two years ago that you now feel are high enough priority that you want to add them to the list.

158
00:16:19,642 --> 00:16:21,345
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's the way that it typically works.

159
00:16:23,339 --> 00:16:26,400
[SPEAKER_03]: And I will say, you know, the process can be difficult to manage.

160
00:16:26,440 --> 00:16:35,823
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a lot of information going back and forth and departments can be on different timelines in terms of when they get information, when grant opportunities open up for them.

161
00:16:36,223 --> 00:16:50,587
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it certainly is, it's a lot of work to manage and, you know, sometimes can be a bit messy as all municipal work can be, but that was the typical process.

162
00:16:50,607 --> 00:16:52,628
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's the process that we followed last year.

163
00:16:54,623 --> 00:16:54,963
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

164
00:16:54,983 --> 00:16:56,785
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I guess that that brings me to my question.

165
00:16:56,865 --> 00:17:04,471
[SPEAKER_04]: So my next question, which is, it sounds like this was kind of a project based assessment.

166
00:17:04,911 --> 00:17:18,221
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm wondering if that would be different from an asset based assessment in the sense that it sounds like we have a list of projects that people think we need, but we maybe don't have a list of all of the city's capital assets and what their actual needs are.

167
00:17:19,302 --> 00:17:20,083
[SPEAKER_04]: Is that correct?

168
00:17:20,163 --> 00:17:22,845
[SPEAKER_04]: Or am I, you know, am I misunderstanding it a little bit?

169
00:17:24,245 --> 00:17:35,290
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, for a department head, a department head should have a list of their capital assets.

170
00:17:36,250 --> 00:17:44,154
[SPEAKER_03]: And they are the experts in their capital assets, and they are the ones who review their capital assets.

171
00:17:44,554 --> 00:17:49,116
[SPEAKER_03]: And then based on the condition, the use, et cetera,

172
00:17:50,975 --> 00:17:54,881
[SPEAKER_03]: define projects that they feel are needed.

173
00:17:56,203 --> 00:18:02,091
[SPEAKER_03]: One thing I will say the Collins Center is not strongly supportive of is

174
00:18:04,593 --> 00:18:08,916
[SPEAKER_03]: Taking a look at asset lists, let's say you have a list of dump trucks, right?

175
00:18:09,816 --> 00:18:19,682
[SPEAKER_03]: There's no, there are guidance, there's best practices around, or I shouldn't say best practices, there are typical lifespans, right?

176
00:18:20,022 --> 00:18:26,666
[SPEAKER_03]: And manufacturers will tell you that this asset has a lifespan of X years, five years, 20 years, whatever it is.

177
00:18:28,978 --> 00:18:30,879
[SPEAKER_03]: And there are guidelines that do exist.

178
00:18:31,059 --> 00:18:36,864
[SPEAKER_03]: So, for example, fire engines and fire ladder trucks have there's guidance from NFPA about

179
00:18:37,969 --> 00:18:44,173
[SPEAKER_03]: how long those should be used on the front line, how long they should be used as backup or second string.

180
00:18:45,073 --> 00:18:55,320
[SPEAKER_03]: But those types of guidelines are great starting points, but they would not really be appropriately used to say, OK, your dump truck is 25 years old.

181
00:18:55,360 --> 00:18:56,720
[SPEAKER_03]: You have to replace it this year.

182
00:18:57,321 --> 00:19:01,723
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some communities, because environmental impacts can be really significant.

183
00:19:02,304 --> 00:19:03,805
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some communities that keep

184
00:19:04,345 --> 00:19:08,210
[SPEAKER_03]: police cruisers for three years, and some communities that keep them for seven years.

185
00:19:08,631 --> 00:19:14,238
[SPEAKER_03]: Dump trucks, likewise, may last 10 years in one environment, but 20 years in another environment.

186
00:19:14,258 --> 00:19:21,587
[SPEAKER_03]: So we don't take, and I'm not sure whether that's what you're referring to when you say an asset-based approach, but the call-in center is not

187
00:19:22,969 --> 00:19:36,375
[SPEAKER_03]: doesn't typically recommend taking a look at an asset inventory divorced from the unique context that the department heads would be able to provide about an asset's condition, performance, etc.

188
00:19:36,395 --> 00:19:37,915
[SPEAKER_03]: Does that answer your question?

189
00:19:39,136 --> 00:19:41,457
[SPEAKER_04]: Kind of, and I appreciate the context.

190
00:19:43,153 --> 00:19:47,175
[SPEAKER_04]: more to me that this the CIP has always felt like step two in a process to me.

191
00:19:47,755 --> 00:19:51,237
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's it sounds to me like step one is kind of just living in people's heads.

192
00:19:51,898 --> 00:19:55,159
[SPEAKER_04]: And and that would be saying here are all of our capital assets.

193
00:19:55,860 --> 00:19:57,080
[SPEAKER_04]: And this is what they're worth.

194
00:19:57,120 --> 00:19:58,301
[SPEAKER_04]: This is how old they are.

195
00:19:58,961 --> 00:20:10,791
[SPEAKER_04]: These are, you know, the issues we have with them and I don't necessarily mean, you know, more replaceable assets like a vehicle more I'm thinking about fixed assets like a building or roads and sidewalks.

196
00:20:11,552 --> 00:20:27,705
[SPEAKER_04]: And, and the reason I'm asking is just like I think it's great to have a capital improvement plan and to say here are the projects that department heads think are the top priority for us to do, but I think the issue that we always have on the council and I think the public has is understanding, how did we get from what is our current condition.

197
00:20:28,265 --> 00:20:47,507
[SPEAKER_04]: to prioritizing specific projects and, and, you know, so that that's why this is always felt like a step two to me, and something that we've been working on as a council is looking at a creating an ordinance for our budget to assess both our operating needs and our capital needs, so that we can have a shared framework and understanding of exactly

198
00:20:48,047 --> 00:21:13,494
[SPEAKER_04]: the facts behind all of that so I don't know if I'm explaining myself entirely correctly but I guess what I'm saying is, you know, step one to me and all of this would be saying, hey every department head, what are all of our capital assets that you manage, put that in one place, then we have a list of all of our assets, then we know, you know, we can say okay Medford High School that's a capital asset we have, you know, what do we think the need is for you know

199
00:21:14,718 --> 00:21:18,480
[SPEAKER_04]: bringing that up, you know, addressing all deferred maintenance on that asset.

200
00:21:18,860 --> 00:21:27,564
[SPEAKER_04]: And then we would come to a capital improvement plan that says so we have 100 million in deferred maintenance at Medford High School and that may be across 10 different projects.

201
00:21:28,024 --> 00:21:34,207
[SPEAKER_04]: Here's our capital improvement plan and the specific projects that we're creating, you know, over the next six fiscal years we're going to create

202
00:21:34,567 --> 00:21:40,693
[SPEAKER_04]: So we're going to do six projects of $10 million and that's going to address 60 million of the 100 million in deferred maintenance.

203
00:21:40,773 --> 00:21:43,035
[SPEAKER_04]: So, you know, sorry I couldn't make that.

204
00:21:43,896 --> 00:21:49,501
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry that was so long winded an explanation but that's really what I'm getting at and I'm wondering what you think about, about that.

205
00:21:50,013 --> 00:21:50,914
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, absolutely.

206
00:21:50,994 --> 00:21:54,856
[SPEAKER_03]: So what you've described has been done.

207
00:21:55,256 --> 00:22:02,240
[SPEAKER_03]: So two years ago, I think I mentioned that we, was the first time I had done the capital improvement plan for the city.

208
00:22:02,360 --> 00:22:07,562
[SPEAKER_03]: Now that project was very different from the project that I've done over the last year.

209
00:22:08,363 --> 00:22:15,627
[SPEAKER_03]: That project was a full in-depth capital improvement planning process that I managed, and it involved

210
00:22:16,918 --> 00:22:22,720
[SPEAKER_03]: interviews with every department head, sitting down with them and saying, what assets do you have in your department?

211
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:30,842
[SPEAKER_03]: Of course, you know, there are asset inventories for vehicles and facilities.

212
00:22:32,223 --> 00:22:38,525
[SPEAKER_03]: There was a chapter that we wrote in the capital improvement plan that we had done two years ago that

213
00:22:39,365 --> 00:22:44,027
[SPEAKER_03]: outlined in pretty good detail all of the capital assets in the city.

214
00:22:45,007 --> 00:22:48,629
[SPEAKER_03]: And you can, I can certainly share that again.

215
00:22:48,649 --> 00:22:56,532
[SPEAKER_03]: That is sort of, it was written for the public so that they could understand how extensive and expansive the capital asset

216
00:22:57,512 --> 00:23:01,194
[SPEAKER_03]: inventory is in the city, you know, the municipally owned capital asset inventory.

217
00:23:01,715 --> 00:23:21,786
[SPEAKER_03]: So there are lists of all of the parks with some basic information, you know, I think acreage and use, lists of the buildings, how many road miles, how many are residential, how many are collector roads, how many bridges, what are the years of the bridges, when were they built, when were they rehabbed, are they, you know, obviously municipally owned,

218
00:23:22,466 --> 00:23:23,747
[SPEAKER_03]: And things like that.

219
00:23:23,827 --> 00:23:25,628
[SPEAKER_03]: So those things do exist.

220
00:23:26,448 --> 00:23:27,108
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

221
00:23:27,128 --> 00:23:29,269
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

222
00:23:29,289 --> 00:23:31,130
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, sorry, go ahead.

223
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:39,193
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I was going to say, and they are also the basis of generating the projects in the capital plan.

224
00:23:41,254 --> 00:23:41,534
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

225
00:23:41,614 --> 00:23:42,335
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, that's helpful.

226
00:23:44,371 --> 00:23:45,512
[SPEAKER_04]: to have that information.

227
00:23:45,832 --> 00:23:52,854
[SPEAKER_04]: Did that document include on the asset inventory list, like the cost it would take for each asset to bring it to a state of good repair?

228
00:23:56,876 --> 00:23:57,336
[SPEAKER_03]: No.

229
00:23:59,897 --> 00:24:05,739
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a difficult question to answer, Councilman, because there

230
00:24:11,828 --> 00:24:12,749
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a great question.

231
00:24:13,409 --> 00:24:19,912
[SPEAKER_03]: And certainly, if there was somebody who was the capital projects manager, that may be something that they could pursue.

232
00:24:19,932 --> 00:24:34,577
[SPEAKER_03]: But it is quite a bit of work and probably something that would not be accomplishable with city human resources, simply because it would be a staggering amount of work to do it that way.

233
00:24:35,678 --> 00:24:38,299
[SPEAKER_03]: What I will say is that the departments

234
00:24:39,079 --> 00:24:44,541
[SPEAKER_03]: staff are the ones who are using the assets all of the time.

235
00:24:45,021 --> 00:24:54,444
[SPEAKER_03]: And so they are working to prioritize, defining the projects that they know are most needed.

236
00:24:55,384 --> 00:25:02,787
[SPEAKER_03]: Certainly there are projects that could be needed, maybe are lower priority, that potentially didn't make it to our list.

237
00:25:02,887 --> 00:25:04,468
[SPEAKER_03]: Although I will say, I think we've got

238
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:10,401
[SPEAKER_03]: I can you I don't want to misstate the number but you'll see it in a few minutes.

239
00:25:10,481 --> 00:25:14,402
[SPEAKER_03]: There are more than 100 projects on the capital plan.

240
00:25:15,482 --> 00:25:18,743
[SPEAKER_03]: And so, certainly, it's quite extensive.

241
00:25:21,183 --> 00:25:27,365
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, that's helpful and I appreciate I understand it's a difficult process but I think you know for us from

242
00:25:27,963 --> 00:25:38,831
[SPEAKER_04]: a city financial planning perspective, there really is a need for us to have that figure you know one of the most helpful documents that we have right now is the road and sidewalk condition and

243
00:25:39,690 --> 00:25:51,158
[SPEAKER_04]: reports and the assessments that came along with that, where we now have an actual dollar number you know over nine figures about how much the city needs to spend to bring our roads and sidewalks into a state of good repair.

244
00:25:51,618 --> 00:25:58,783
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think for financial planning purposes, you know, having something like that for all of our assets really needs to be a goal and I know it's not your job to

245
00:25:59,603 --> 00:26:00,143
[SPEAKER_04]: to do that.

246
00:26:00,183 --> 00:26:03,444
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'm not asking you to obviously speak towards that.

247
00:26:03,504 --> 00:26:08,645
[SPEAKER_04]: But it sounds like we have a lot of really great data from the last process that you did and from this process.

248
00:26:09,245 --> 00:26:20,848
[SPEAKER_04]: And that, you know, pulling all that together and working potentially with an outside consultant to really nail down the dollar figures for what the needs are for capital needs.

249
00:26:20,888 --> 00:26:23,149
[SPEAKER_04]: The dollar amount needs for capital needs is important.

250
00:26:23,509 --> 00:26:29,210
[SPEAKER_04]: And completely hear you on department heads, you know, knowing their assets the best and suggesting what the best

251
00:26:30,170 --> 00:26:46,997
[SPEAKER_04]: most urgent needs are for capital funding but you know I think exactly what you just said about you know there may be other lower priority needs that don't get included, that's what we need to know about to you know the capital improvement is to me, how much we're investing and trying to bring us back to a state of good repair.

252
00:26:47,497 --> 00:26:52,318
[SPEAKER_04]: but the figure that we don't have is what actually would everything in a state of good repair be.

253
00:26:52,719 --> 00:26:55,980
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's what we need to be able to benchmark progress in my opinion.

254
00:26:56,060 --> 00:27:09,924
[SPEAKER_04]: So just putting that out there, I completely understand your role in the process and that most of what I said is not your role, but I really appreciate your expertise and giving me the details I need to better understand what we need to get to the place that I'm talking about.

255
00:27:09,964 --> 00:27:10,684
[SPEAKER_04]: So thank you very much.

256
00:27:11,384 --> 00:27:23,227
[SPEAKER_03]: I will say that the pavement condition index is an absolutely vital tool that was also grant funded and was a great process for the city to go through.

257
00:27:23,247 --> 00:27:26,868
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's great.

258
00:27:28,169 --> 00:27:33,170
[SPEAKER_03]: It would be amazing if you had that type of report for each asset type.

259
00:27:34,531 --> 00:27:48,892
[SPEAKER_03]: The other type of assessment that municipalities often do is to hire an architectural firm that can come in and do really deep facilities assessments, you know, the facade,

260
00:27:49,553 --> 00:27:57,319
[SPEAKER_03]: all of the HVAC, the plumbing, all of that, and they can generate that number that you'd be looking for for facilities.

261
00:27:57,660 --> 00:28:14,774
[SPEAKER_03]: Of course, that's quite a costly endeavor to bring in a consultant to do that, but I absolutely agree it's an invaluable tool not only for city council, but also for the department heads to help them understand what is the true cost and is there anything that I'm just not seeing.

262
00:28:14,794 --> 00:28:16,475
[SPEAKER_03]: I really appreciate your comments.

263
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:19,000
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

264
00:28:19,060 --> 00:28:19,881
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, and could you.

265
00:28:20,021 --> 00:28:45,833
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry to Bogart I know I'm my other fellow counselor the question but just how often that that the index, the either the process that you did at the beginning where you surveyed all the department has to get capital needs or the thing that we did for roads and sidewalk conditions how often would you suggest we do that iteratively, should it be every five year capital improvement plan we also do that, or should it be more more regular or less regular.

266
00:28:47,902 --> 00:28:55,387
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that just feasibly, every five years is a great target.

267
00:28:55,447 --> 00:29:11,998
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, the thing about the pavement condition index, and certainly your DPW and engineering staff can talk more specifically about it, is if you, and just like any plan, say you do a road assessment, and then you say, oh, that's great, look at all that money we need to spend, and then you don't,

268
00:29:12,698 --> 00:29:18,681
[SPEAKER_03]: follow up with the actual investment or try to get close to it, then the PCI becomes very stale.

269
00:29:19,021 --> 00:29:37,110
[SPEAKER_03]: But if you're updating it and your staff know how to say, yes, we did do that road, let's put in the new PCI for that road, and it shows you and it's sort of constantly updated, then you have a better chance of stretching out how often you need to do that sort of consulting project.

270
00:29:37,510 --> 00:29:38,131
[SPEAKER_03]: Does that make sense?

271
00:29:38,971 --> 00:29:39,612
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much.

272
00:29:39,672 --> 00:29:40,172
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, thank you.

273
00:29:40,597 --> 00:29:40,817
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

274
00:29:40,837 --> 00:29:43,960
[SPEAKER_02]: We have a question from Councilor saying and then we'll go to Councilor Carvio after that.

275
00:29:44,961 --> 00:29:45,361
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

276
00:29:45,701 --> 00:29:54,729
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, so, I think, Councilor bears made some great points about needing to look at our assets and as a whole.

277
00:29:55,530 --> 00:30:03,437
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, I think something that runs through my mind, as well as that there might be important projects that are important to residents in the city but, um,

278
00:30:04,818 --> 00:30:07,439
[SPEAKER_00]: They might not have the resources to reach out to city government.

279
00:30:07,479 --> 00:30:09,020
[SPEAKER_00]: They might not know who to go to.

280
00:30:09,100 --> 00:30:17,304
[SPEAKER_00]: And so there might be a disconnect in a way between what we hear at City Hall versus what residents on the ground want.

281
00:30:18,324 --> 00:30:22,866
[SPEAKER_00]: And of course, I do trust our department heads to know best what types of projects we need.

282
00:30:23,266 --> 00:30:33,651
[SPEAKER_00]: But I was wondering if what you saw is the role of community feedback and resident engagement in this process.

283
00:30:34,066 --> 00:30:36,968
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, thank you so much for asking that, Councilor Seng.

284
00:30:37,008 --> 00:30:40,050
[SPEAKER_03]: It's such an important component of capital planning.

285
00:30:40,551 --> 00:30:58,103
[SPEAKER_03]: So there are a couple of different ways that residents can contribute to the capital planning process, because the capital plan is actually built on all sorts of other plans that already exist or should exist.

286
00:30:58,543 --> 00:31:00,265
[SPEAKER_03]: So just I'll give you one example.

287
00:31:01,400 --> 00:31:07,428
[SPEAKER_03]: The municipalities in Massachusetts are all required if they want to get certain grants to have an open space and recreation plan.

288
00:31:08,469 --> 00:31:15,838
[SPEAKER_03]: And that plan, a master plan, and various other types of plans are really

289
00:31:17,192 --> 00:31:22,895
[SPEAKER_03]: processes that are deeply, deeply, or should be deeply engaging with the community.

290
00:31:23,515 --> 00:31:33,180
[SPEAKER_03]: And municipalities have really, I think, in the last number of years, kind of expanded their view of what engagement means.

291
00:31:33,240 --> 00:31:38,883
[SPEAKER_03]: It doesn't just mean saying there's going to be a meeting, posting an agenda, and saying, hey, we have a public meeting.

292
00:31:38,923 --> 00:31:39,944
[SPEAKER_03]: Come if you find out.

293
00:31:40,084 --> 00:31:41,985
[SPEAKER_03]: Come if you come to the website and find out about it.

294
00:31:42,585 --> 00:31:45,067
[SPEAKER_03]: It's really more proactive than that.

295
00:31:45,468 --> 00:31:53,455
[SPEAKER_03]: And so cities and towns in Massachusetts have been doing a decent job of trying to really build out their capital engagement capacity.

296
00:31:53,756 --> 00:31:58,680
[SPEAKER_03]: And that means going, say you have a charrette, you know, or say you have a

297
00:31:59,581 --> 00:32:10,807
[SPEAKER_03]: A charrette's like a meeting, for those who don't know, a charrette's like a meeting where people can come and really deeply engage with planning and land use type of activities.

298
00:32:11,328 --> 00:32:20,133
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it might mean something like going to, leaving City Hall and bringing that charrette activity to a community center.

299
00:32:20,853 --> 00:32:22,874
[SPEAKER_03]: or a school where people are comfortable.

300
00:32:23,134 --> 00:32:27,697
[SPEAKER_03]: They may not be comfortable going to City Hall, but they may be comfortable going to their child's school to participate.

301
00:32:28,217 --> 00:32:33,260
[SPEAKER_03]: It also means offering meetings in different languages to meet people where they are.

302
00:32:33,440 --> 00:32:41,404
[SPEAKER_03]: It may mean something as small as providing child care so that people with young families where kids can't be left alone can participate.

303
00:32:41,464 --> 00:32:43,225
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's such an important part

304
00:32:43,925 --> 00:32:47,789
[SPEAKER_03]: So the capital planning process is built on those types of plans.

305
00:32:48,169 --> 00:33:02,563
[SPEAKER_03]: So when you're planning development and sustainability department provides me with the list of park projects that they see as priorities, what they're doing is referencing the plans that have been built with strong community engagement.

306
00:33:03,023 --> 00:33:03,723
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's one thing.

307
00:33:04,664 --> 00:33:15,769
[SPEAKER_03]: But the other thing, which is really interesting, is that I've seen in some municipalities a more robust direct community engagement with the capital planning process.

308
00:33:16,209 --> 00:33:23,953
[SPEAKER_03]: And it could be something like, now we didn't do this, but it's something that you could consider in the future, something along the lines of

309
00:33:25,313 --> 00:33:33,736
[SPEAKER_03]: creating a form, a Google form or a digital form, where residents can contribute ideas for capital improvements.

310
00:33:34,516 --> 00:33:42,518
[SPEAKER_03]: And they're not going to be able to tell you how much the road is going to cost, how much asphalt you need, but they're going to be able to tell you, hey, if this road's not on your list, it should be.

311
00:33:43,178 --> 00:33:48,600
[SPEAKER_03]: Or they may tell you, I'm really disappointed that the school playgrounds are not accessible.

312
00:33:48,760 --> 00:33:54,244
[SPEAKER_03]: And that might trigger the departments to say, oh, yes, I'm seeing a lot of conversation.

313
00:33:54,304 --> 00:33:58,006
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm hearing a lot from community members that this is important.

314
00:33:58,687 --> 00:34:00,188
[SPEAKER_03]: And that could elevate a project.

315
00:34:01,448 --> 00:34:03,470
[SPEAKER_03]: And there may be other ways to engage

316
00:34:03,950 --> 00:34:05,091
[SPEAKER_03]: community members.

317
00:34:05,151 --> 00:34:15,458
[SPEAKER_03]: So you could look for individuals, but you could also go to community-based organizations that maybe speak for a larger demographic group and say, hey, what are you seeing?

318
00:34:15,859 --> 00:34:24,065
[SPEAKER_03]: Any capital needs that you see could be PTAs, it could be religious groups, it could be, you know, different affinity groups.

319
00:34:24,905 --> 00:34:30,247
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's a really interesting and innovative way of engaging the public in the capital planning process.

320
00:34:30,627 --> 00:34:38,190
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, not something that's very widespread, but something that's on the cutting edge, something that I'd absolutely recommend that you all consider.

321
00:34:39,691 --> 00:34:49,535
[SPEAKER_03]: And if you have more questions about that, I'd be happy to think about who I know in other cities and towns that have done things similar, and maybe we can make a connection.

322
00:34:51,298 --> 00:34:52,019
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you so much.

323
00:34:52,159 --> 00:34:58,704
[SPEAKER_00]: I think you read my mind on the next question, which is that, you know, we do have a lot of plans, and I was wondering how this plan engaged with those plans.

324
00:34:59,445 --> 00:35:11,255
[SPEAKER_00]: I have tons of questions, but I know you have more to present, so I'll let you get to that, but I did have a question because we started to talk a little bit about prioritization.

325
00:35:12,136 --> 00:35:23,652
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I was wondering if there were metrics that we were using to evaluate how we prioritize projects or if it was really, you know, left up to department heads or to these plans.

326
00:35:24,397 --> 00:35:36,507
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so the Collins Center does have what we call a scoring methodology, which has a number of parameters with which we score projects.

327
00:35:36,588 --> 00:35:40,891
[SPEAKER_03]: And there are things that you would expect, things like, is there a public safety issue?

328
00:35:42,152 --> 00:35:45,095
[SPEAKER_03]: Does this project advance environmental concerns?

329
00:35:45,215 --> 00:35:47,697
[SPEAKER_03]: Does it have an economic development benefit to the town?

330
00:35:47,877 --> 00:35:49,679
[SPEAKER_03]: Is there external funding available?

331
00:35:49,699 --> 00:35:50,279
[SPEAKER_03]: Things like that.

332
00:35:52,280 --> 00:36:04,324
[SPEAKER_03]: In this particular case, the process we went through in the past year, what we did was we were able to essentially accommodate all, basically all of the projects that the department heads identified.

333
00:36:04,864 --> 00:36:07,704
[SPEAKER_03]: We just spread it actually over seven years.

334
00:36:07,724 --> 00:36:17,307
[SPEAKER_03]: So there were a handful of projects that got pushed out to FY29, but we were able to accommodate basically all of the projects that departments

335
00:36:17,687 --> 00:36:19,047
[SPEAKER_03]: identified as priorities.

336
00:36:20,188 --> 00:36:21,648
[SPEAKER_03]: And so that was really great.

337
00:36:21,688 --> 00:36:24,368
[SPEAKER_03]: But we do have that scoring methodology that goes through.

338
00:36:24,389 --> 00:36:27,869
[SPEAKER_03]: I can't remember if it's 15 parameters or 19, something like that.

339
00:36:28,769 --> 00:36:32,910
[SPEAKER_03]: And those are really, and department prioritization is one of the very important ones.

340
00:36:34,931 --> 00:36:38,512
[SPEAKER_03]: But those are, that scoring is very useful for

341
00:36:40,392 --> 00:36:44,074
[SPEAKER_03]: for guiding a conversation, especially if financial resources are tight.

342
00:36:44,514 --> 00:36:55,741
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, I will say in this particular case, we've had a special, you know, very unique funding source, ARPA, which has really changed the game in terms of

343
00:36:56,561 --> 00:37:01,584
[SPEAKER_03]: you know, these couple of years where we can spend it on capital needs.

344
00:37:01,844 --> 00:37:03,765
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's a little bit of an anomaly.

345
00:37:04,685 --> 00:37:12,730
[SPEAKER_03]: And so the scoring becomes less imperative, because there are a lot of resources out there.

346
00:37:13,530 --> 00:37:20,637
[SPEAKER_03]: But yes, absolutely, you need to have some sort of methodology that allows you to assess objectively the different projects.

347
00:37:20,757 --> 00:37:24,320
[SPEAKER_03]: And if there are financial constraints, you have to make difficult decisions.

348
00:37:24,360 --> 00:37:30,725
[SPEAKER_03]: And sometimes it can be really challenging to say, well, what's more important, you know, a dump truck or three new cruisers?

349
00:37:30,765 --> 00:37:33,848
[SPEAKER_03]: Like they're both super important, both absolutely essential.

350
00:37:33,908 --> 00:37:37,851
[SPEAKER_03]: So how do we make that work within a financially feasible plan?

351
00:37:38,192 --> 00:37:39,473
[SPEAKER_03]: It can be a challenge.

352
00:37:44,453 --> 00:37:45,634
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll go to Councilor Carviel.

353
00:37:46,395 --> 00:37:47,416
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Madam President.

354
00:37:47,957 --> 00:37:49,559
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you sir for the presentation so far.

355
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:56,267
[SPEAKER_07]: I agree with Councilor Baez and what he said it earlier that I think maybe we are putting the cart in front of the horse here a little bit.

356
00:37:58,289 --> 00:38:02,294
[SPEAKER_07]: Being on this council longer than anybody else, I've seen capital plans come and go in this community.

357
00:38:03,700 --> 00:38:08,783
[SPEAKER_07]: We see them, we develop them, and they never really ever come to fruition.

358
00:38:09,103 --> 00:38:11,245
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe one or two things ever happen on them.

359
00:38:11,265 --> 00:38:21,911
[SPEAKER_07]: But I think the city is at the point where right now is, I think we need to take stock of our assets and see where they are and the condition that they're in.

360
00:38:24,132 --> 00:38:27,915
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a history in this community of letting our assets

361
00:38:28,695 --> 00:38:29,816
[SPEAKER_07]: just really fall apart.

362
00:38:30,457 --> 00:38:42,431
[SPEAKER_07]: So over the last six years, or maybe a little longer, we have a brand new DPW building, we have a new police station, and we have a new library.

363
00:38:42,572 --> 00:38:48,218
[SPEAKER_07]: And before then, the only really capital improvements that we ever did was we built

364
00:38:49,019 --> 00:38:59,388
[SPEAKER_07]: the new schools, and now those, those schools are 20 plus years old, and we didn't do our job as as as a city and maintain them.

365
00:39:00,629 --> 00:39:06,494
[SPEAKER_07]: So I say, so I think you'll tell me his idea of, let's, let's get our assets

366
00:39:07,518 --> 00:39:13,963
[SPEAKER_07]: down on paper, see what condition they are, and then we can develop our priorities and know where we have to go.

367
00:39:14,364 --> 00:39:18,828
[SPEAKER_07]: And my other question is, do we have the staff

368
00:39:20,037 --> 00:39:23,140
[SPEAKER_07]: to see the capital improvement plans coming through.

369
00:39:24,001 --> 00:39:27,084
[SPEAKER_07]: Every department we have right now is short staffed here.

370
00:39:27,905 --> 00:39:31,909
[SPEAKER_07]: Some departments don't even have department heads.

371
00:39:32,329 --> 00:39:36,853
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's a concern that I share with the capital plan going forward.

372
00:39:37,334 --> 00:39:41,478
[SPEAKER_07]: So just my opinion for the next few minutes and then I'll come back with some more questions after.

373
00:39:42,582 --> 00:39:43,503
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, excellent.

374
00:39:43,543 --> 00:39:45,264
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you for those comments, Councilman.

375
00:39:46,305 --> 00:39:47,686
[SPEAKER_03]: I think you're absolutely right.

376
00:39:47,886 --> 00:39:54,611
[SPEAKER_03]: Just to go to your last point first, you need to have the staff to manage projects.

377
00:39:54,751 --> 00:40:05,639
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, some projects can be done in-house to a large degree, but most of them need to be, you need to procure experts to do them.

378
00:40:06,220 --> 00:40:08,841
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you need to provide oversight for those

379
00:40:09,842 --> 00:40:11,043
[SPEAKER_03]: those contractors.

380
00:40:11,163 --> 00:40:15,026
[SPEAKER_03]: And so you do need human resources to manage a capital plan.

381
00:40:15,406 --> 00:40:16,006
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

382
00:40:16,066 --> 00:40:22,410
[SPEAKER_03]: And that is a challenge for Medford and many cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

383
00:40:23,431 --> 00:40:31,376
[SPEAKER_03]: And the other issue with human resources is directly tied to your point about deferred maintenance.

384
00:40:33,137 --> 00:40:46,937
[SPEAKER_03]: Many communities can spend a decade moving toward a major construction of a new building, and it's a lot of work, and getting everybody to buy in, figuring out how we're going to fund it, maybe pursuing a debt exclusion.

385
00:40:48,078 --> 00:41:03,205
[SPEAKER_03]: But then if you don't have the staff to do the regular preventive maintenance on the building, checking those HVAC filters, cleaning things, and just monitoring what's going on with the systems, then they're not going to last as long as they should.

386
00:41:03,606 --> 00:41:07,888
[SPEAKER_03]: And so that's a really significant challenge for cities and towns around the Commonwealth.

387
00:41:07,968 --> 00:41:10,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Those costs fall within the operating budget.

388
00:41:11,430 --> 00:41:20,178
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, obviously you guys know very well how challenging developing the operating budget and funding what really needs to be funded can be.

389
00:41:20,198 --> 00:41:24,022
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

390
00:41:24,082 --> 00:41:26,965
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe that's the questions we have for now, if you want to proceed.

391
00:41:27,385 --> 00:41:28,006
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, thank you.

392
00:41:28,847 --> 00:41:29,107
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

393
00:41:33,492 --> 00:41:42,595
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, actually this is a this is a good slide to come up next, you know, to the to the to the counselors points about what are the capital assets in Bedford.

394
00:41:43,035 --> 00:41:51,578
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a summary that comes from the chapter that I had mentioned to a few minutes ago.

395
00:41:51,998 --> 00:41:52,118
[SPEAKER_03]: So,

396
00:41:53,118 --> 00:41:56,401
[SPEAKER_03]: In Medford, there are a lot of capital assets that are municipally owned.

397
00:41:57,162 --> 00:42:03,147
[SPEAKER_03]: There are more than a dozen city-owned buildings, police, fire stations, library, city hall, DPW yard.

398
00:42:03,888 --> 00:42:08,772
[SPEAKER_03]: There are nine school facilities and associated components like athletic fields and parking lots.

399
00:42:09,953 --> 00:42:13,756
[SPEAKER_03]: You have IT assets, computers, tablets, network components.

400
00:42:14,557 --> 00:42:22,606
[SPEAKER_03]: And then there are many, many vehicles, trailers, mowers, sedans, police cruisers, dump trucks, fire engines, ladder trucks.

401
00:42:22,666 --> 00:42:28,933
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, these run the gamut from a $15,000 trailer to a million dollar ladder truck.

402
00:42:29,033 --> 00:42:32,096
[SPEAKER_03]: So many, many vehicles across multiple departments.

403
00:42:32,917 --> 00:42:40,641
[SPEAKER_03]: You have dozens of parks and recreation sites, including playgrounds, trails, athletic courts, athletic fields, pool, pond, skating rink.

404
00:42:41,261 --> 00:42:47,984
[SPEAKER_03]: You have a lot of recreational assets in the city, and a lot of them need capital improvement.

405
00:42:48,885 --> 00:42:52,506
[SPEAKER_03]: You also have passive use open space like veteran squares and monuments.

406
00:42:54,437 --> 00:42:55,638
[SPEAKER_03]: cemeteries, things like that.

407
00:42:56,298 --> 00:43:05,084
[SPEAKER_03]: You have 92 miles of roads and many, many, many, many miles of sidewalks that need to be maintained and improved from time to time.

408
00:43:05,824 --> 00:43:07,546
[SPEAKER_03]: There are two city-owned bridges.

409
00:43:08,946 --> 00:43:13,089
[SPEAKER_03]: There are countless culverts, drainage pipes, and there's even a dam.

410
00:43:13,689 --> 00:43:16,531
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you have your water distribution and sewer collection systems.

411
00:43:17,092 --> 00:43:21,434
[SPEAKER_03]: So there are a lot of assets.

412
00:43:21,475 --> 00:43:23,656
[SPEAKER_03]: The counselor mentioned the pavement

413
00:43:26,098 --> 00:43:28,361
[SPEAKER_03]: road assessment, that's one very common one.

414
00:43:28,821 --> 00:43:43,557
[SPEAKER_03]: As I mentioned, facilities are also typically, well maybe I shouldn't say typically, it's not uncommon for cities and towns to bring in architectural firms to assess, do a facilities assessment on their facilities.

415
00:43:44,318 --> 00:43:50,102
[SPEAKER_03]: Water and sewer systems often will have assessments done by professional engineering firms.

416
00:43:50,522 --> 00:44:00,848
[SPEAKER_03]: So those are the kind of first places I would guide you toward if you are serious about finding some money to bring in specialized consultants to take a look at your assets.

417
00:44:01,228 --> 00:44:03,390
[SPEAKER_03]: Those are the ones that are most commonly targeted.

418
00:44:03,410 --> 00:44:13,216
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to shift and talk about the

419
00:44:14,380 --> 00:44:15,462
[SPEAKER_03]: investment strategy.

420
00:44:15,482 --> 00:44:19,648
[SPEAKER_03]: And GF is a short way of saying general fund.

421
00:44:20,269 --> 00:44:24,395
[SPEAKER_03]: So this is general fund only, it doesn't include the enterprise funds, water and sewer.

422
00:44:26,200 --> 00:44:30,942
[SPEAKER_03]: So the capital investment strategy is based on historical data.

423
00:44:31,262 --> 00:44:37,885
[SPEAKER_03]: Trend analysis is obviously a foundation of a lot of financial projections and planning.

424
00:44:38,685 --> 00:44:51,631
[SPEAKER_03]: So here we look at three years of historical capital investment, and we compare that to the net budget, which is reported to the state on the recap sheet.

425
00:44:53,014 --> 00:44:54,315
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'm going to walk you through this table.

426
00:44:55,015 --> 00:44:58,657
[SPEAKER_03]: The top boxes are the existing capital investment.

427
00:44:58,917 --> 00:45:03,099
[SPEAKER_03]: So the first line is your existing net general fund non-excluded debt.

428
00:45:03,839 --> 00:45:10,362
[SPEAKER_03]: And when I say net, that means that if you have any subsidies, like from revolving funds, things like that, that's all netted out.

429
00:45:10,702 --> 00:45:15,384
[SPEAKER_03]: So in 21, 22, 23, those were your debt service figures for the general fund.

430
00:45:17,607 --> 00:45:19,749
[SPEAKER_03]: Then you have a capital lease for a fire truck.

431
00:45:20,389 --> 00:45:27,054
[SPEAKER_03]: And in 2022 and 2023, half of that capital lease was funded from the general fund operating budget.

432
00:45:28,655 --> 00:45:33,618
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you also have what is typically called pay-go spending or pay-as-you-go spending.

433
00:45:33,999 --> 00:45:36,661
[SPEAKER_03]: That's cash that's spent on capital projects.

434
00:45:37,301 --> 00:45:39,683
[SPEAKER_03]: Most likely and most typically, it's free cash.

435
00:45:42,413 --> 00:45:44,974
[SPEAKER_03]: So I've added that as a note, free cash.

436
00:45:45,634 --> 00:45:50,196
[SPEAKER_03]: So 2021, 2022, there was no free cash spending, which I think is an anomaly.

437
00:45:50,796 --> 00:45:58,198
[SPEAKER_03]: In 2023, so far, there's been slightly over 2.9 million appropriated from free cash for capital projects.

438
00:45:59,118 --> 00:46:10,462
[SPEAKER_03]: So the line there that says total existing capital investment, that's the total of all the money you've spent from the general fund on capital projects for those three historical years.

439
00:46:11,969 --> 00:46:19,356
[SPEAKER_03]: And then moving down to the second box, the first line there says net budget with a 4% projected annual growth figure.

440
00:46:20,677 --> 00:46:24,100
[SPEAKER_03]: We calculate net budget using the recap sheet from the state.

441
00:46:25,181 --> 00:46:33,209
[SPEAKER_03]: And we're using 4% as the projected annual growth moving, you know, as we move into the future, 24, 25, et cetera.

442
00:46:33,589 --> 00:46:37,673
[SPEAKER_03]: But what you see in these boxes is the actual net budget.

443
00:46:39,515 --> 00:46:43,058
[SPEAKER_03]: The next line says funded via debt as a percent of net budget.

444
00:46:43,178 --> 00:46:46,682
[SPEAKER_03]: So that means what is your debt service as a percent of your net budget?

445
00:46:47,362 --> 00:46:51,766
[SPEAKER_03]: And as you can see, it's somewhere, it's between three and 3.15%.

446
00:46:51,867 --> 00:46:56,851
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a typical number.

447
00:46:57,111 --> 00:46:58,753
[SPEAKER_03]: It is a strong number.

448
00:46:59,794 --> 00:47:01,255
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not too low, it's not too high.

449
00:47:01,275 --> 00:47:04,218
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's a good number for the city.

450
00:47:23,973 --> 00:47:24,574
[SPEAKER_03]: for FY23.

451
00:47:25,774 --> 00:47:29,295
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the total capital spending as a percentage of net budget.

452
00:47:29,416 --> 00:47:30,596
[SPEAKER_03]: So you can see those totaled up.

453
00:47:32,177 --> 00:47:37,799
[SPEAKER_03]: So the bullet at the bottom just has some notes about kind of what we interpreted from the findings.

454
00:47:38,059 --> 00:47:45,362
[SPEAKER_03]: So historically, the city has invested approximately three and a half percent of net budget in capital projects, both from debt and cash.

455
00:47:47,607 --> 00:47:55,511
[SPEAKER_03]: ARPA funds have significantly impacted the CIP that was developed two years ago and significantly changed things.

456
00:47:57,412 --> 00:48:09,036
[SPEAKER_03]: Because ARPA is cash, we can fund projects that previously may have been funded with debt, but now we have the opportunity to fund them with cash, saving the taxpayers dollars because they're not having to pay interest on those projects.

457
00:48:10,557 --> 00:48:12,518
[SPEAKER_03]: And it really is a significant opportunity.

458
00:48:15,382 --> 00:48:18,305
[SPEAKER_03]: Before I go to the next slide, I just want to make sure there are no questions about this.

459
00:48:18,325 --> 00:48:19,666
[SPEAKER_03]: Did I explain it well enough?

460
00:48:22,148 --> 00:48:22,648
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe so.

461
00:48:22,668 --> 00:48:23,709
[SPEAKER_02]: I do not see any questions.

462
00:48:24,410 --> 00:48:24,730
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

463
00:48:27,392 --> 00:48:27,753
[SPEAKER_03]: All right.

464
00:48:27,833 --> 00:48:38,322
[SPEAKER_03]: So taking the historical data, conversing with the finance team about what they're seeing in terms of operating budget projections, their financial forecasting, et cetera.

465
00:48:39,537 --> 00:48:46,465
[SPEAKER_03]: We developed a three pronged approach to the general fund capital investment strategy for the ensuing six years, five years.

466
00:48:47,583 --> 00:48:48,683
[SPEAKER_03]: So one, free cash.

467
00:48:49,224 --> 00:48:57,146
[SPEAKER_03]: We want to project free cash for capital investment conservatively because we really need to protect reserve levels.

468
00:48:57,266 --> 00:49:02,227
[SPEAKER_03]: It's sort of been an economic whiplash from the start of the pandemic to today.

469
00:49:02,287 --> 00:49:03,608
[SPEAKER_03]: There were dire projections.

470
00:49:03,688 --> 00:49:05,328
[SPEAKER_03]: Then it turned out things weren't so bad.

471
00:49:05,688 --> 00:49:07,229
[SPEAKER_03]: Now we have all this ARPA money.

472
00:49:07,709 --> 00:49:10,210
[SPEAKER_03]: But what does the future hold in terms of the economy?

473
00:49:10,910 --> 00:49:18,201
[SPEAKER_03]: We really don't know, but we do know that it's best practice, and it makes sense, and particularly in this case, to project conservatively.

474
00:49:18,361 --> 00:49:24,411
[SPEAKER_03]: So we don't want to spend too much of our free cash because we want to keep some of it back to be held in reserve just in case we need it.

475
00:49:25,765 --> 00:49:29,648
[SPEAKER_03]: The second prong of the strategy is those ARPA dollars.

476
00:49:30,528 --> 00:49:34,911
[SPEAKER_03]: ARPA is really a unique opportunity to accelerate capital investment in the city.

477
00:49:35,431 --> 00:49:40,054
[SPEAKER_03]: And there are some rules around when it needs to be committed and when it needs to be expended.

478
00:49:40,174 --> 00:49:51,042
[SPEAKER_03]: And so you'll see that there's quite a lot of projects that are accomplished or have already been sort of committed.

479
00:49:51,182 --> 00:49:52,923
[SPEAKER_03]: We've already committed a lot of our ARPA dollars.

480
00:49:53,243 --> 00:49:59,952
[SPEAKER_03]: But then there's more that will be committed through this plan for capital spending.

481
00:50:00,593 --> 00:50:02,296
[SPEAKER_03]: That is not something that's going to last forever.

482
00:50:02,396 --> 00:50:03,477
[SPEAKER_03]: Obviously, there are time limits.

483
00:50:03,558 --> 00:50:07,042
[SPEAKER_03]: But for the next several years, it's a key part of the plan.

484
00:50:08,172 --> 00:50:10,533
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the third is the general fund debt.

485
00:50:11,093 --> 00:50:24,160
[SPEAKER_03]: So our target says that we're going to try to keep general fund debt service at 3% of net budget to maintain affordability for residents and also to avoid significant up and down swings in the annual debt service payments.

486
00:50:24,500 --> 00:50:29,002
[SPEAKER_03]: And that really is essential for operating budget development.

487
00:50:30,824 --> 00:50:35,786
[SPEAKER_03]: In addition, the plan calls for water and sewer projects to be fully funded from enterprise fund revenues.

488
00:50:36,166 --> 00:50:44,190
[SPEAKER_03]: So the enterprise fund is set up to run those services just like a business would, and it needs to cover all of its costs.

489
00:50:44,630 --> 00:50:48,972
[SPEAKER_03]: And so there are two sources that the enterprise fund can use to pay for its capital projects.

490
00:50:49,032 --> 00:50:52,654
[SPEAKER_03]: They have retained earnings, which is equivalent to free cash.

491
00:50:53,254 --> 00:51:00,337
[SPEAKER_03]: And so any cash funded projects would be typically funded with retained earnings, and then they can also issue debt.

492
00:51:01,902 --> 00:51:14,758
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the last piece of the plan, which is something that the city does really well is to continue to be aggressive and seeking grants, including MSBA and any other non tax levy funding sources.

493
00:51:15,398 --> 00:51:18,702
[SPEAKER_03]: Obviously, this is something that just makes a ton of sense.

494
00:51:19,303 --> 00:51:21,664
[SPEAKER_03]: for taxpayers.

495
00:51:22,405 --> 00:51:33,551
[SPEAKER_03]: And there are a lot of opportunities at the state level that the city has a strong history of being very competitive for grants.

496
00:51:34,291 --> 00:51:45,357
[SPEAKER_03]: And we're sort of entering a new era of opportunity from the federal government with the bipartisan infrastructure law, just kind of opening up the doors for a lot of infrastructure investment.

497
00:51:45,637 --> 00:51:51,099
[SPEAKER_03]: And I actually think the city of Medford is really well positioned to take advantage of those opportunities.

498
00:51:56,021 --> 00:51:57,602
[SPEAKER_03]: All right, so here's another table.

499
00:51:57,622 --> 00:52:04,084
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm going to walk you through it because I want to make sure that folks can understand and don't get confused.

500
00:52:04,705 --> 00:52:07,786
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm going to move you guys so I can see this fully.

501
00:52:10,508 --> 00:52:15,555
[SPEAKER_03]: The top is the same as the last table.

502
00:52:15,675 --> 00:52:21,062
[SPEAKER_03]: That's existing capital investment, but it goes out to future years.

503
00:52:21,302 --> 00:52:22,223
[SPEAKER_03]: So it includes 24, 25, 26, 27, 28.

504
00:52:25,071 --> 00:52:32,475
[SPEAKER_03]: So we know, because the debt that you're issuing is long-term debt, we can project what those costs are going to be.

505
00:52:33,055 --> 00:52:37,577
[SPEAKER_03]: And we can see that the debt changes over time.

506
00:52:38,818 --> 00:52:41,419
[SPEAKER_03]: And we can also project capital leases.

507
00:52:42,539 --> 00:52:47,822
[SPEAKER_03]: Here we have the lease for the fire truck listed in FY23.

508
00:52:48,843 --> 00:52:50,243
[SPEAKER_03]: There are several more years of that.

509
00:52:50,323 --> 00:52:52,764
[SPEAKER_03]: And those lease payments are actually included.

510
