01:10:51,456 --> 01:10:58,521
[SPEAKER_03]: So this pie chart just simply shows of all of those projects and the project costs, how are they going to be funded?

681
01:10:58,581 --> 01:11:07,527
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is, I think, an important slide to share, really important for residents to understand kind of where money might be coming from.

682
01:11:08,693 --> 01:11:12,476
[SPEAKER_03]: So we'll look at 12 o'clock here.

683
01:11:12,536 --> 01:11:17,220
[SPEAKER_03]: That blue pie slice is free cash.

684
01:11:17,480 --> 01:11:17,760
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's 4%.

685
01:11:19,041 --> 01:11:20,743
[SPEAKER_03]: Then we've got ARPA, which is 7%.

686
01:11:22,344 --> 01:11:28,929
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, a pretty significant, unique, one-time situation that we're in with ARPA.

687
01:11:29,810 --> 01:11:35,452
[SPEAKER_03]: Then we have the green chunk, which is funded through general fund debt.

688
01:11:35,892 --> 01:11:42,454
[SPEAKER_03]: So that is that 57% of the project costs are general fund debt projects, over $98 million.

689
01:11:42,474 --> 01:11:42,834
[SPEAKER_03]: That does include

690
01:11:48,362 --> 01:11:51,525
[SPEAKER_03]: $50.6 million for the Medford High project.

691
01:11:51,625 --> 01:12:03,536
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, to the councilor's point, at this point, not including any MSBA dollars, which is obviously a very conservative approach, better to have that number come in lower for the city side.

692
01:12:03,636 --> 01:12:06,398
[SPEAKER_03]: But nonetheless, that $50 million is in there.

693
01:12:06,518 --> 01:12:12,364
[SPEAKER_03]: And then we've got $21 million for fire department stations, training facility construction.

694
01:12:12,864 --> 01:12:20,211
[SPEAKER_03]: So those two projects are obviously a significant portion of that $98 million, that $71 million for those two projects.

695
01:12:23,220 --> 01:12:27,161
[SPEAKER_03]: The purple pie slice, the 3%, is Enterprise Fund PAYGO projects.

696
01:12:27,642 --> 01:12:34,224
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the light blue slice, that 2%, is Enterprise Fund debt projects.

697
01:12:34,624 --> 01:12:45,648
[SPEAKER_03]: The Enterprise Fund debt projects are, by and large, funded through a privileged MWRA, Mass Water Resources Authority loan program.

698
01:12:45,828 --> 01:12:48,289
[SPEAKER_03]: And so there are certain benefits to using debt

699
01:12:50,070 --> 01:12:56,052
[SPEAKER_03]: in it through that program, because you get, you know, kind of special interest and interest rates and all that.

700
01:12:56,112 --> 01:13:00,953
[SPEAKER_03]: The 27%, which again, I want to make sure people are really listening, because I think that this is really impressive.

701
01:13:00,973 --> 01:13:16,818
[SPEAKER_03]: And again, it goes back to all of the work that the departments are doing to identify grants and really pursue them in particular, you know, your planning, development and sustainability department that pursues all sorts of state and federal grants to really invest in the

702
01:13:17,859 --> 01:13:20,821
[SPEAKER_03]: recreation and cultural assets that you have here in the city.

703
01:13:21,261 --> 01:13:31,348
[SPEAKER_03]: So that orange slice is 27%, it's $45 million, and it represents all of the other non-general fund dollars.

704
01:13:31,848 --> 01:13:37,192
[SPEAKER_03]: So it includes Chapter 90, which is obviously the road funding from the state.

705
01:13:37,712 --> 01:13:45,938
[SPEAKER_03]: It includes CPA, linkage, state and federal earmarks, which is something that is obviously really great for the administration to pursue.

706
01:13:46,458 --> 01:13:51,360
[SPEAKER_03]: It includes all sorts of state and federal grants like park grants, CDBG, complete streets.

707
01:13:52,261 --> 01:13:54,882
[SPEAKER_03]: I can't even name all of the different grants that are in there.

708
01:13:55,262 --> 01:14:12,929
[SPEAKER_03]: But I just want to make sure that folks understand, you know, any residents who are listening, the departments are really working hard to access those grants and really leverage the dollars that taxpayers contribute to maximize how much money they can bring to the city from the state and federal government.

709
01:14:16,688 --> 01:14:18,349
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Madam President.

710
01:14:19,130 --> 01:14:21,292
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we have a list of those 217 projects?

711
01:14:23,153 --> 01:14:25,275
[SPEAKER_03]: I do have that list and it will be shared.

