827
01:25:04,360 --> 01:25:07,742
[SPEAKER_03]: I will point out that you can see that there are deficits.

828
01:25:08,482 --> 01:25:13,865
[SPEAKER_03]: So what that is telling us is that starting in FY 25 and 26, we are spending more than that 3% target.

829
01:25:13,885 --> 01:25:16,987
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, in 25 and 26, the numbers are not so bad.

830
01:25:17,007 --> 01:25:19,188
[SPEAKER_03]: $50,000 over on a budget of $5.5 million is not

831
01:25:28,235 --> 01:25:40,405
[SPEAKER_03]: very concerning, but once the construction of the, the potential construction of the fire project and the high school project kind of go forward, that's a pretty big number.

832
01:25:40,766 --> 01:25:44,989
[SPEAKER_03]: That's not going to be ever feasible to accomplish within the 3% target.

833
01:25:46,230 --> 01:25:55,903
[SPEAKER_03]: And so what I've already, you know, chatted with the mayor and the finance team about is the fact that we need to keep an eye on those projects and understand how are we moving forward.

834
01:25:56,324 --> 01:25:59,708
[SPEAKER_03]: Are we going to get the MSBA loans or grants?

835
01:25:59,928 --> 01:26:01,330
[SPEAKER_03]: Are we, you know, are we

836
01:26:01,951 --> 01:26:07,913
[SPEAKER_03]: looking at a debt exclusion for one of these projects, which comes obviously with a dedicated funding source.

837
01:26:07,953 --> 01:26:11,195
[SPEAKER_03]: So just so you know, that's why those deficits exist.

838
01:26:11,295 --> 01:26:15,056
[SPEAKER_03]: They're driven largely by those major building projects.

839
01:26:15,676 --> 01:26:21,759
[SPEAKER_03]: And it's not really going to be possible to do those projects and keep to the 3% target, even if you

840
01:26:25,260 --> 01:26:28,021
